  "body": "### What's your issue about?\r\n`__default__` fallback function produces an incompatible ABI output from the equivalent Solidity contract. Unsure what the \"correct\" functionality is per ABIv2 (cc @davesque), but this is a problem for integration with external tooling.\r\n\r\nFor example, this Solidity program:\r\n```javascript\r\ncontract Untitled\r\n{\r\n    function () external {\r\n        revert();\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\nproduces:\r\n```json\r\n{\"payable\": false,\"stateMutability\": \"nonpayable\",\"type\": \"fallback\"}\r\n```\r\nwhereas this Vyper program:\r\n```python\r\n@public\r\ndef __default__():\r\n    assert False\r\n```\r\nproduces:\r\n```json\r\n{\"name\": \"__default__\",\"outputs\": [],\"inputs\": [],\"constant\": false,\"payable\": false,\"type\": \"function\"}\r\n```\r\n\r\n### How can it be fixed?\r\n- Investigate ABIv2 expectations for the \"fallback\" function feature\r\n- Remove field \"name\" from ABI output (in Vyper, as in Python, `__[underscored_names]__` should *never* be used externally)\r\n- Change the \"type\" field to \"fallback\"\r\n- It appears that the fallback cannot have the fields \"inputs\" or \"outputs\" as it does not decode data explicitly (leaving it to internal use of #1181 to decode passed data)\r\n\r\nRelated to #1244",
